This paper deals with algorithms and data structures for manipulating edge-labelled pseudo-triangulations, which are a type of geometric object commonly studied in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves analyzing the number of flips required to transform one pseudo-triangulation into another, which is a problem related to data structures and algorithms. Hence, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial arguments and techniques, which are related to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also involves studying the properties of convex layers and convex hulls, which are related to cs.GR (Graphics) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
